<center><table border=0><tr><td><center><H2><font face=arial>Re: Alignment, PvP, EQ Final</font></H2></center>
<font face=arial size=2><b>Posted By:</b> <A HREF="/cgi-local/whois2.cgi?Stupid">Stupid</a><br>
<b>Posted On:</b> 4:31 a.m. 19/2/1999<br>
<b>Subject:</b> Re: Alignment, PvP, EQ Final<p>
<br><center><img src="http://www.everworld.net/pvpquest/images/divider.gif" width=452 height=22 border=0></center><BR><P ALIGN=CENTER><b>In Reply To:</b> <A HREF="http://www.everworld.net/cgi-local/pvp.cgi?read=1047" TARGET=_self>Alignment, PvP, EQ Final</A> (Platinum)
</STRONG><FONT SIZE=2 color=#FFFFFF FACE=arial>
<P>> I agree with this, however one point i made in the alignment doc

<BR>&gt; is that it would be based upon the faction system. I used
<BR>&gt; standard RPG models along with the faction model to create this.
<BR>&gt; The major difference the player would see is their character
<BR>&gt; assigned a 'word' defining their alignment, however these words
<BR>&gt; would simply be representative of a faction number or range of
<BR>&gt; numbers. For example, a Good player could have a faction rating
<BR>&gt; of 500, the character would see 'good' on their screen, but the
<BR>&gt; server would read 500. I understand that Verant wants to stick
<BR>&gt; with a numerical system, however that does not change much of
<BR>&gt; the alignment system, and in no way diminishes its importance.
<P>The way I understand the faction system is that there exist many different factions, each with a different rating. For example, a player might have a rating of 128 in the Qeynos Guard faction, a rating of 358 in the Blackburrow Gnoll faction, a rating of 792 in the Oggok Warrior faction and countless others which range from "kill on sight" to "roll out the red carpet". Faction ratings are not a single number, but rather a whole slew of numbers, each of which is both inter-related to the others, but also treated uniquely.
<P>How can this kind of variety be summarized into a single word (or number)?
</FONT></td></tr></table></P>
